From 1 January to 12 December this year, soldiers confiscated 26 tonnes of illegal drugs. CAPE TOWN - The South African National Defence Force (SANDF) has stepped up the pressure on cross border criminals and their efforts appear to be paying off.From 1 January to 12 December this year, soldiers confiscated 26 tonnes of illegal drugs.Fifteen companies are stationed along the country s borders with Botswana, Lesotho, Mozambique, Namibia, Swaziland and Zimbabwe. SANDF spokesperson Lieutenant Colonel Piet Paxton said: This year was a great success if we measure this against last year s figures. For example, we had a very success in terms of contraband entering South Africa. The bulk of that a big haul in April where we confiscated 29,000 pairs of fake running shoes. Paxton says the number of people who enter the country illegally by cutting through fences along the border decreased from 80 per month to 14. We managed to stop also just short of 16,000 people entering the country illegally - undocumented - and those people are then handed over to the Department of Home Affairs for the processing or repatriation. (Edited by Winnie Theletsane)